<!-- livebook:{"persist_outputs":true} -->

# Recursion Schemes

```elixir
Mix.install([
  {:kino, "~> 0.19.0"}
])
```

## Introduction

[**Recursion schemes**](https://github.com/passy/awesome-recursion-schemes) are higher order functions that can be used as building blocks for composing recursive algorithms. Recursion schemes separate the *recursive part* of a recursive algorithm from the *actual calculation* the same way that functions like `Enum.map` separate the the *iteration* logic on the container from the *calculation* that is done on each individual element.

This livebook will be guiding you through a thought process to understanding recursion schemes by inventing/discovering them by yourself.

## Recap: Higher Order Functions — recursion vs map

Before we start lets revisit a well known higher order function: `Enum.map`. Originally rooted in functional programming, nowadays it is commonly used in imperative and object oriented programming languages as well. It allows to express an element-wise operation over some container object, like over a list or an array of elements.

Take a look at the following three example functions. The first one walks through a list recursively to multiply each element by two, collecting the results in a new list.

```elixir
defmodule Recursion do
  def doubleEachElement([]), do: []

  def doubleEachElement([head | tail]) do
    [2 * head | doubleEachElement(tail)]
  end
end

[1, 2, 3]
|> Recursion.doubleEachElement()
|> IO.inspect(label: "Doubled")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Doubled: [2, 4, 6]
```

The next one does the same but but uses an accumultor to eagerly build the resulting list.

```elixir
defmodule TailRecursion do
  def doubleEachElement(list, accumulator \\ [])

  def doubleEachElement([], accum), do: accum

  def doubleEachElement([head | tail], accum) do
    doubleEachElement(tail, [2 * head | accum])
  end
end

[1, 2, 3]
|> TailRecursion.doubleEachElement()
|> IO.inspect(label: "Doubled")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Doubled: [6, 4, 2]
```

The next one achieves the same result but splits the task of iteration and the task of element-wise calculation into two separate functions. The function doing the interation and collecting the resulting values is called `List.map`, or typically just `map`.

```elixir
defmodule GenericListMap do
  def processEachElement(list, op, accumulator \\ [])

  def processEachElement([], _op, accum), do: accum

  def processEachElement([head | tail], op, accum) do
    processEachElement(tail, op, [op.(head) | accum])
  end
end

[1, 2, 3]
|> GenericListMap.processEachElement(fn e -> 2 * e end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Doubled")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Doubled: [6, 4, 2]
```

```elixir
[1, 2, 3]
# using the builtin Enum.map
|> Enum.map(fn e -> 2 * e end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Doubled")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Doubled: [2, 4, 6]
```

There are many advantages of separating the iteration from the element-wise calculation. The most obvious advantage is that the iteration has only to be defined once and can be reused for various different operations:

```elixir
[1, 2, 3]
|> GenericListMap.processEachElement(fn e -> 3 * e end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Tripled")

[1, 2, 3]
|> GenericListMap.processEachElement(fn e -> e + 1 end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Incremented")

[1, 2, 3]
|> GenericListMap.processEachElement(fn e -> rem(e, 2) == 0 end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Even")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Tripled: [9, 6, 3]
Incremented: [4, 3, 2]
Even: [false, true, false]
```

Another advantage is that the intentions and invariants of the task are expressed more clearly and explcitly. Applying the map function will not change the number of elements in the array and it will not change the order of the elements.

A third advantage of this conceptual separation is to abstract away the specific iteration stragegy, like the specific usage of a for loop (vs a while loop or some other iteration logic). It allowes for later changes and optimizations. For example the internal iteration order could be reversed or even parallelized without effecting the observable result:

```elixir
defmodule ParallelMap do
  def processEachElement(list, op) do
    parent = self()

    pids =
      for item <- list do
        # for each element spawn a new process to do the calculation
        spawn(fn ->
          send(parent, {self(), op.(item)})
        end)
      end

    for pid <- pids do
      receive do
        # collect all the results back into the final list
        {^pid, result} -> result
      end
    end
  end
end

[1, 2, 3]
# from the calling perspective it looks exactly the same
|> ParallelMap.processEachElement(fn e -> 3 * e end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Tripled")

[1, 2, 3]
# from the calling perspective it looks exactly the same
|> ParallelMap.processEachElement(fn e -> e + 1 end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Incremented")

[1, 2, 3]
# from the calling perspective it looks exactly the same
|> ParallelMap.processEachElement(fn e -> rem(e, 2) == 0 end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Even")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Tripled: [3, 6, 9]
Incremented: [2, 3, 4]
Even: [false, true, false]
```

The fourth advantage is that the same concept of applying an element-wise transformation can be implemented for other containers of elements. For example for a binary tree as the one below:

```elixir
simpleBinaryTree = {
  :inner,
  {:inner, {:leaf, 2}, {:leaf, 3}},
  {:inner, {:leaf, 5}, {:inner, {:leaf, 2}, {:leaf, 3}}}
}

simpleBinaryTree |> IO.inspect(label: "Tree of Tuples", width: 35, pretty: true)
Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Tree of Tuples: {:inner,
 {:inner, {:leaf, 2}, {:leaf, 3}},
 {:inner, {:leaf, 5},
  {:inner, {:leaf, 2}, {:leaf, 3}}}}
```

A corresponding map function could be implemented as follows:

```elixir
defmodule TreeMap do
  # takes a tree and a operation to apply to each element
  def processEachElement(tree, op)

  def processEachElement({:leaf, value}, op) do
    # if the tree is just a leaf, apply op the the containg value
    # and build a new leaf
    {:leaf, op.(value)}
  end

  def processEachElement({:inner, left, right}, op) do
    # if the tree is an inner node, call the function recursively on each child
    # and build a new inner node from both results
    {
      :inner,
      processEachElement(left, op),
      processEachElement(right, op)
    }
  end
end

Kino.nothing()
```

Then we coule use the `TreeMap.processEachElement` function in the same way (except for the name) as we did with the `GenericListMap.processEachElement` function before to transform each element in the tree:

```elixir
simpleBinaryTree |> IO.inspect(label: "Original Tree")
IO.puts("")

simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeMap.processEachElement(fn e -> 3 * e end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Tripled", pretty: true)

IO.puts("")

simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeMap.processEachElement(fn e -> e + 1 end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Incremented", pretty: true)

IO.puts("")

simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeMap.processEachElement(fn e -> rem(e, 2) == 0 end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Even", pretty: true)

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Original Tree: {:inner, {:inner, {:leaf, 2}, {:leaf, 3}},
 {:inner, {:leaf, 5}, {:inner, {:leaf, 2}, {:leaf, 3}}}}

Tripled: {:inner, {:inner, {:leaf, 6}, {:leaf, 9}},
 {:inner, {:leaf, 15}, {:inner, {:leaf, 6}, {:leaf, 9}}}}

Incremented: {:inner, {:inner, {:leaf, 3}, {:leaf, 4}},
 {:inner, {:leaf, 6}, {:inner, {:leaf, 3}, {:leaf, 4}}}}

Even: {:inner, {:inner, {:leaf, true}, {:leaf, false}},
 {:inner, {:leaf, false}, {:inner, {:leaf, true}, {:leaf, false}}}}
```

Now we have seen that separating the stepping from the work to do at each step is a powerful abstraction when doing computations on each element in a data structure.

## Recursive data structures

With the *binary tree* in the example above we have seen that the corresponding `TreeMap.processEachElement` function allowes us to work with a recursive data structure without re-implementing the recursive walking part our self each time.

But by the nature of the `TreeMap.processEachElement` function we were constraint to modify each value of the tree separately. At each step in the callback function we only have access to one element of the tree, not to its parents, children or other parts of the tree. What if we want to do actual tree-related calculations but still package the walking the tree part into a neatly reusable function?

Lets take a look at a few typical cases to see if we can recognize some pattern. Say we want to determine the height of the tree, count the leafs of the tree, count the total number of nodes, find the minimum value inside the tree and find the maximum value inside the tree. We also want to serialize our tree into a string, for better readability

Lets first implement one function for each of our goals by hand. Afterwards we will try to find similaries in the recursion structure and come up with a general reusable solution.

For the maximum tree height, at each node we calculate the height of both children and take their maximum:

```elixir
defmodule TreeHeight do
  def treeHeight(tree)

  # height of a leaf is 1
  def treeHeight({:leaf, _value}) do
    1
  end

  # height of an inner node is one more than the height of its higher children
  def treeHeight({:inner, left, right}) do
    1 +
      max(
        treeHeight(left),
        treeHeight(right)
      )
  end
end

Kino.nothing()
```

```elixir
simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeHeight.treeHeight()
|> IO.inspect(label: "Tree Height")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Tree Height: 4
```

For the total number of leafs the result is 1 if the node itself is a leaf. For inner nodes we sum the number of leafs of the left child with the number of leafs of the right child:

```elixir
defmodule TreeLeafCount do
  def count(tree)

  # a leaf counts as 1
  def count({:leaf, _value}) do
    1
  end

  # inner nodes do not count as leafs but just sum the count of their cildren
  def count({:inner, left, right}) do
    count(left) + count(right)
  end
end

simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeLeafCount.count()
|> IO.inspect(label: "Leaf Count")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Leaf Count: 5
```

For the total node count we do the same as for counting the leafs but we also add +1 in case of the inner node, to count this node as well.

```elixir
defmodule TreeNodeCount do
  def count(tree)

  # leafs count as one
  def count({:leaf, _value}) do
    1
  end

  # inner nodes count as 1 as well
  def count({:inner, left, right}) do
    1 + count(left) + count(right)
  end
end

simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeNodeCount.count()
|> IO.inspect(label: "Node Count")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Node Count: 9
```

For the minimum value stored in a tree (mind our tree currently stores values only in its leafs), we take the minimum of either the left or the right child tree. For leaf nodes we just take their value.

```elixir
defmodule TreeMinValue do
  def minValue(tree)

  # for leaf nodes there is just one value to take
  def minValue({:leaf, value}) do
    value
  end

  # inner nodes take the minimum of either of their childrens minimum
  def minValue({:inner, left, right}) do
    min(
      minValue(left),
      minValue(right)
    )
  end
end

simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeMinValue.minValue()
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Min Value: 2
```

For the maximum value stored in a tree (mind our tree stores values only in its leafs), we do the same as for the minimum value, but taking the maximum of two children:

```elixir
defmodule TreeMaxValue do
  def maxValue(tree)

  def maxValue({:leaf, value}) do
    value
  end

  def maxValue({:inner, left, right}) do
    max(
      maxValue(left),
      maxValue(right)
    )
  end
end

simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeMaxValue.maxValue()
|> IO.inspect(label: "Max Value")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Max Value: 5
```

For turning the `Tree` into a `String` the concat the stringified left child to the stringified right child of an `:inner` node. For `:leaf` nodes we turn the value stored in the node into a `String`. We also append some parenthisis to reflect the tree structure in the `String`.

```elixir
defmodule TreeToString do
  def toString(tree)

  def toString({:leaf, value}) do
    "[#{value}]"
  end

  def toString({:inner, left, right}) do
    "(#{toString(left)}:#{toString(right)})"
  end
end

simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeToString.toString()
|> IO.inspect(label: "Tree as String")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Tree as String: "(([2]:[3]):([5]:([2]:[3])))"
```

All the implementations above look very similar. All of them check if the current node we are looking at is a `:leaf`. If so, a base case result is returned, either a constant or a some other value based only on the value stored in the `{:leaf, _}` tuple. If on the other hand the current node is an `:inner` node, two recursive function calls are invoked (one for the left and one for the right branch of the tree) and then their result is combined in a suitable way.

This pattern of similarity between these function is what we are after. 
Such recognizable commonalities between different recursive algorithms is exactly what is called a recursion scheme.

The specific pattern that we just recognized is one specific recursion scheme. Later we will see that this pattern is already well known and has its own name.

Lets try to extract this pattern of recursive function calls into a common function, similar to our `TreeMap.processEachElement` function.

We will take one of the function definitions above and try to move all the specific calculations into callback function parameters to make them configurable.

```elixir
defmodule TreeReducer do
  # takes a tree and two operations
  # one for processing leaf nodes and one for processing inner nodes
  def reduce(tree, leafOp, innerOp)

  # if the tree is just a leaf
  # we pass the value to leafOp
  def reduce({:leaf, value}, leafOp, _innerOp) do
    leafOp.(value)
  end

  # if the tree is an inner node
  # we process the left and the right child separatly and pass both results
  # to innerOp
  def reduce({:inner, left, right}, leafOp, innerOp) do
    innerOp.(reduce(left, leafOp, innerOp), reduce(right, leafOp, innerOp))
  end
end

Kino.nothing()
```

Instead of hardcoding what exactly to do with the `:leaf` nodes and how exactly the recursive results for the two branches of `:inner` nodes are to be combined, we accept two callback functions.

`handleLeaf/1` is called with the value stored in each `{:leaf, value}` tuple, similar to `op` in our `TreeMap.processEachElement` function from before.

`handleBranch/2` is called with the two results from both of the recursive calls.

Now be can express all of our different tree-based calculations from before in terms of our new `TreeReducer.reduce/3` function:

```elixir
simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeReducer.reduce(fn _ -> 1 end, &(1 + max(&1, &2)))
|> IO.inspect(label: "Tree Height")

simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeReducer.reduce(fn _ -> 1 end, &(&1 + &2))
|> IO.inspect(label: "Leaf Count")

simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeReducer.reduce(fn _ -> 1 end, &(1 + &1 + &2))
|> IO.inspect(label: "Node Count")

simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeReducer.reduce(fn v -> v end, &min(&1, &2))
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeReducer.reduce(fn v -> v end, &max(&1, &2))
|> IO.inspect(label: "Max Value")

simpleBinaryTree
|> TreeReducer.reduce(fn v -> "[#{v}]" end, &"(#{&1}, #{&2})")
|> IO.inspect(label: "Tree as String")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Tree Height: 4
Leaf Count: 5
Node Count: 9
Min Value: 2
Max Value: 5
Tree as String: "(([2], [3]), ([5], ([2], [3])))"
```

That worked great! We have successfully abstracted the recursion pattern into a single `TreeReducer.reduce/3` function.

*Are we done yet?*

Have we mastered the recursion scheme? Almost, but we can find **even more patterns**!

## Other recursive data structures

The `TreeReducer.reduce/3` function does work for our specfic binary tree. 
But what if we have other recursive data structures to work with?

For example *linked lists*, *trees with more than two branches* or *trees with values stored on the inner nodes* as well?

It would be great if we could come up with a single `Magic.reduce` function that works the same for all of these structures, the same way that the interface of a `Enum.map(collection, map)` functions works for both `List` and `Stream` (and `Arrays`, `Trees`, and other collections, depending on the programming language, in general `map` works on all types that are `Functors`)

Lets write down some recursive data structures that we can come up with and start from there:

## simpleBinaryTreeWithInnerValues

Trees with values store in both leafs and inner nodes:

```elixir
simpleBinaryTreeWithInnerValues = {
  :inner,
  4,
  {:inner, 8, {:leaf, 23}, {:leaf, 42}},
  {:inner, 16, {:leaf, 32}, {:inner, 64, {:leaf, 108}, {:leaf, 99}}}
}

simpleBinaryTreeWithInnerValues |> IO.inspect(label: "Tree of Tuples with inner values")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Tree of Tuples with inner values: {:inner, 4, {:inner, 8, {:leaf, 23}, {:leaf, 42}},
 {:inner, 16, {:leaf, 32}, {:inner, 64, {:leaf, 108}, {:leaf, 99}}}}
```

## simpleLinkedList

```elixir
simpleLinkedList = {42, {23, {16, {8, {4, {}}}}}}

simpleLinkedList |> IO.inspect(label: "simpleLinkedList")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
simpleLinkedList: {42, {23, {16, {8, {4, {}}}}}}
```

## simpleBinaryTreeWithEmptyNode

```elixir
simpleBinaryTreeWithEmptyNode = {
  :inner,
  4,
  {:inner, 8, {:leaf, 23}, :empty},
  {:inner, 16, :empty, {:inner, 42, :empty, {:leaf, 108}}}
}

simpleBinaryTreeWithEmptyNode |> IO.inspect(label: "Tree of Tuples with inner values")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Tree of Tuples with inner values: {:inner, 4, {:inner, 8, {:leaf, 23}, :empty},
 {:inner, 16, :empty, {:inner, 42, :empty, {:leaf, 108}}}}
```

Based on these three examples our next goal is again to recognize a pattern between all these structures. A pattern that can then be generalized.

Lets try to implement a function to find the minimum element for each of these three structures.

Afterwards we will try to see a common pattern between all of the three implementations:

```elixir
defmodule BinaryTreeMinValue do
  def minValue(tree)

  # The minimum of just a leaf is justs its value
  def minValue({:leaf, value}) do
    value
  end

  # The minimum of an inner node is:
  # the smallest value of either: its own value, the minimum of the left
  # sub tree or the minimum of the right sub tree
  def minValue({:inner, inner_value, left, right}) do
    inner_value
    |> min(minValue(left))
    |> min(minValue(right))
  end
end

simpleBinaryTreeWithInnerValues
|> BinaryTreeMinValue.minValue()
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Min Value: 4
```

```elixir
defmodule LinkedListMinValue do
  # linked lists can be empty
  # empty lists have no minimum that could be the result
  # so we might provide a fallback value  
  def minValue(list, fallback \\ :infinity)

  # if the list is empty just return the fallback value
  def minValue({}, fallback) do
    fallback
  end

  # if the list consists of a head value
  # and a remaining tail, we take the minimum
  # between the head to the minimum of the tail
  def minValue({head, tail}, fallback) do
    min(
      head,
      minValue(tail, fallback)
    )
  end
end

simpleLinkedList
|> LinkedListMinValue.minValue()
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Min Value: 4
```

```elixir
defmodule SparseBinaryTreeMinValue do
  # A sparse tree may contain empty nodes
  # As with empty linked lists we need a fallback value
  # to always produce a result
  def minValue(tree, fallback \\ :infinity)

  # for empty nodes the result is just the fallback
  def minValue(:empty, fallback) do
    fallback
  end

  # for leafs the minimum value is just the one value stored
  # in the node
  def minValue({:leaf, value}, _fallback) do
    value
  end

  # for inner nodes we calculate the minimum for each of both sub tree
  # and compare each result to the value at the inner node itself
  def minValue({:inner, inner_value, left, right}, fallback) do
    inner_value
    |> min(minValue(left, fallback))
    |> min(minValue(right, fallback))
  end
end

simpleBinaryTreeWithEmptyNode
|> SparseBinaryTreeMinValue.minValue(:infinity)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Min Value: 4
```

WWe can observe that each of theses functions differ in the number of branches, depending on the the recursive data structure.

For the `LinkedList` we need only two branches, one for the empty `{}` case at the end of the list and one for the case of list being `{head, tail}` pair.

For the `BinaryTree` there are thre cases: either an `:inner` node with left/right children, or an `:empty` node, or a `:leaf` node with a single value. The recursive function needs to handle each of the three conditions.

Also the number of arguments of the functions vary. For the `BinaryTree` that contains *at least one leaf node with a value* we do *not* need a `fallback` value. For the other two structures we need a `fallback` value. This is because in case the structure itself might not contain any value that could be relied on to use as result.

*How could we possibly unify all three of these functions into a common interface?*

Lets take it slowly and first implement a generic function for each of the three structures individually again, as we did with `TreeReducer.reduce` before.

For processing the `BinaryTree` we need to accept two callbacks:

* one for handling the `:leaf`
* and one for handling the `:inner` node:

```elixir
defmodule BinaryTreeReduce do
  # takes a tree and two callbacks
  def reduceValue(tree, handleLeaf, handleInner)

  # if the tree is a leaf node, pass the single value to the one callback
  def reduceValue({:leaf, value}, handleLeaf, _handleInner) do
    handleLeaf.(value)
  end

  # if the tree is an inner node, process each child separatly recursively
  # and pass both result to the second callback
  def reduceValue({:inner, inner_value, left, right}, handleLeaf, handleInner) do
    handleInner.(
      inner_value,
      reduceValue(left, handleLeaf, handleInner),
      reduceValue(right, handleLeaf, handleInner)
    )
  end
end

simpleBinaryTreeWithInnerValues
# needs to be called with both callbacks at once
|> BinaryTreeReduce.reduceValue(
  fn l -> l end,
  fn v, l, r -> min(v, min(l, r)) end
)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Min Value: 4
```

For processing the `LinkedList` we also accept two callbacks:

* one for handling the empty `{}` case
* and one for handling the `{head, tail}`.

Notice that for handling the fallback case of an empty list we will accept it not as constant value but as function returning a constant. This is for consistency reasons.

```elixir
defmodule LinkedListReduce do
  # takes a list and two callbacks
  def reduceValue(list, handleEmpty, handleInner)

  # if the list is empty we call the one callback
  def reduceValue({}, handleEmpty, _handleInner) do
    handleEmpty.()
  end

  # if the list is not empt we process the tail recursively
  # and then pass both head value and the recursion result
  # to the second callback
  def reduceValue({head, tail}, handleEmpty, handleInner) do
    handleInner.(
      head,
      reduceValue(tail, handleEmpty, handleInner)
    )
  end
end

simpleLinkedList
|> LinkedListReduce.reduceValue(fn -> :infinity end, &min/2)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Min Value: 4
```

For the `Tree` with maybe `:empty` nodes we had to consider three cases (`:inner`, `:leaf`, and `:empty`). 
Therefore we will accept three different callback functions to handle them. 
Same as with the `LinkedList` above, we model the fallback value for the empty case as constant-returning-function.

```elixir
defmodule SparseTreeReduce do
  # accept the tree and 3 callbacks
  def reduceValue(tree, handleEmpty, handleLeaf, handleInner)

  # if empty call the one callback
  def reduceValue(:empty, handleEmpty, _handleLeaf, _handleInner) do
    handleEmpty.()
  end

  # for leaf nodes pass the single value to the second callback 
  def reduceValue({:leaf, value}, _handleEmpty, handleLeaf, _handleInner) do
    handleLeaf.(value)
  end

  # for inner nodes, first prcocess the two child tree recursively
  # then pass both recursion results and the value from the inner node
  # to the third callback
  def reduceValue({:inner, value, left, right}, handleEmpty, handleLeaf, handleInner) do
    handleInner.(
      value,
      reduceValue(left, handleEmpty, handleLeaf, handleInner),
      reduceValue(right, handleEmpty, handleLeaf, handleInner)
    )
  end
end

simpleBinaryTreeWithEmptyNode
# we need to provide three callbacks
|> SparseTreeReduce.reduceValue(
  fn -> :infinity end,
  & &1,
  fn v, l, r -> min(v, min(l, r)) end
)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Min Value: 4
```

Now we can see even more cleary that the number of needed handle-callbacks for each reduction vary and that even the number of argument each of these handle-callback takes, varies. For example `handleEmpty` takes no arguments but `handleInner` for the one `Tree` excpects 3 arguments.

At a first glance it does not seem possible to unify the arguments of these different reduction function into a single generic function that works for both lists, trees and other recursive data strutures.

**But now comes the brilliant idea** (not mine):

What if we could merge all the different callback functions into a *single* callback function and leave it for *this single function* to handle each possible case correctly? Lets try:

```elixir
defmodule BinaryTreeReduceUnified do
  # take the tree and a single callback
  def reduceValue(tree, handleCases)

  # if the tree is just a leaf
  # pass the value to the single callback
  # together with a :leaf to tell the callback 
  # that the value is from a leaf
  def reduceValue({:leaf, value}, handleCases) do
    handleCases.({:leaf, value})
  end

  # if its an inner node,
  # process the child trees recursively as before
  # but this pass the result to the same one callback
  # together with an :inner marker to signify the the parameters come from 
  # an inner node
  def reduceValue({:inner, inner_value, left, right}, handleCases) do
    handleCases.({
      :inner,
      inner_value,
      reduceValue(left, handleCases),
      reduceValue(right, handleCases)
    })
  end
end

simpleBinaryTreeWithInnerValues
# now I have to provide only a single callback
|> BinaryTreeReduceUnified.reduceValue(fn
  # the one callback function handles both cases
  {:leaf, v} -> v
  {:inner, v, l, r} -> min(v, min(l, r))
end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Min Value: 4
```

Same for `LinkedList`:

```elixir
defmodule LinkedListReduceUnified do
  # take a list and a single callback
  def reduceValue(list, handleCases)

  # for empty lists just pass an empty marker to the callback
  def reduceValue({}, handleCases) do
    handleCases.({})
  end

  # for {head, tail} pairs, process the tail recursively
  # and pass the result and the head together as tuple
  # to the single callback
  def reduceValue({head, tail}, handleCases) do
    handleCases.({
      head,
      reduceValue(tail, handleCases)
    })
  end
end

simpleLinkedList
# again only a single callback
|> LinkedListReduceUnified.reduceValue(fn
  # handling both casese
  {} -> :infinity
  {a, b} -> min(a, b)
end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Min Value: 4
```

```elixir
defmodule SparseTreeReduceUnified do
  def reduceValue(tree, handleCases)

  def reduceValue(:empty, handleCases) do
    handleCases.(:empty)
  end

  def reduceValue({:leaf, value}, handleCases) do
    handleCases.({:leaf, value})
  end

  def reduceValue({:inner, value, left, right}, handleCases) do
    handleCases.({
      :inner,
      value,
      reduceValue(left, handleCases),
      reduceValue(right, handleCases)
    })
  end
end

simpleBinaryTreeWithEmptyNode
# again only a single callback
|> SparseTreeReduceUnified.reduceValue(fn
  # handling all three casese
  :empty -> :infinity
  {:leaf, v} -> v
  {:inner, v, l, r} -> min(v, min(l, r))
end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Min Value: 4
```

Did you notice what we did here? We merged all the callback functions into a *single*  `handleCases` callback that in each case takes *only a single value as argument*.

What what exactly is this argument that we pass to handleCases? It is either an object containing the results of the recusive function calls, or the value store in the leafs of the data structure, in case we hit a base case, or a special marker object in case we are in an empty case.

**But look again:** The value we pass to `handleCases` does reflect exactly the structure of the respective node we are processing.

For example when processing an `:inner` node of a binary `Tree` with inner values (`{:inner, value, left, right}`), we call handleCases((`{:inner, value, left, right})`) with `value` containing the value in the current node, but `left` and `right` *not* being the sub trees of the original tree, but instead the *already calculated results* of the two recursive calls.

What we pass to the handleCases looks *on the surface structurally* exactly like a node of the the `Tree` but, instead of actually containing the recursive structure of the `Tree`, it is just a flat `Tuple` for packaging the results of the recursive function calls.

For each of our data structures we can think of actually working with two *different but matching storage structures*:

* The one that stores the *actual* `Tree`
* and one that stores the *result of a single recursive calculation step* at one tree node.

Both look like `{:inner, value, left, right} or {:leaf, value}` on the surface but differ in their content: For the one storing the actual `Tree` `left` and `right` themself are `Tree`s. For the one that contains the  recursion result `left` and `right` are of type `Number`.

In other words the one structure is actually `{:inner, value: Number, left: Tree, right: Tree} | {:leaf, value: number}` and the other is: `{value: Number, left: Number, right: Number} | {value: number}`.

```elixir
defmodule Ellipsis do 
  # Just a helper to allow writing ... in code
  def ..., do: nil
end
Kino.nothing()
```

```elixir
import Ellipsis

actualInnerTreeNode = {
  :inner,
  # value stored in this node
  5,
  # left child, being itself a tree node recursively
  {...},
  # right child, being itself a tree node recursively 
  {...}
}

# a container object storing the results of recursive function calls
recursionResultTreeNode = {
  # has the structure as the actual corresponding tree node
  :inner,
  # copy of the value stored in the original tree node,
  5,
  # not a recursive child node, 
  23,
  # but just the result of the recursive function call on the 
  # left child of the original tree node
  # not a recursive child node, but just the result of the 
  42
  # recursive function call on the right child of the original tree node 
}

# an actual node from the recursive tree structure
actualTreeLeafNode = {
  :leaf,
  # value stored in this node,
  5
}

# a container object storing the results of recursive function calls
# but this is the base case so it does not store any results
recursionResultTreeLeftNode = {
  # has the same property keys as the actual corresponding tree node
  :leaf,
  #  copy of the value stored in the original tree node
  5
}

Kino.nothing()
```

By accident we came up with a helper structure for passing results between recursive calculations.

So by mirroring the structure of the recursive tree nodes we can capture all the results of our recursive function calls an pass it to to our handler function as a single value. The `handleCases` function can then pattern match on the marker to tell on which case of the structure the recursion is currently working in.

This perspective allows us to define generic recursive functions that work for any recursive data structure as long as for each data structure we make use of the corresponding *matching result containg*.

**But there is more!** Take another look at the each of the `handleCases.(...)` function calls and get ready for one more unifying abstraction. Below are copies of the `SparseTreeReduceUnified.reduceValue`, `LinkedListReduceUnified.reduceValue`, and `TreeReduceUnified.reduceValue` functions but now annotated with some comments to highlight some repeatitions in the code.

```elixir
defmodule SparseTreeReduceUnifiedReview do
  def reduceValue(tree, handleCases) do
    case tree do
      # inspect type of current node <------
      :empty ->
        # with flat copy of the node structure <------
        :empty
        # call handleCases
        |> then(handleCases)

      # inspect type of current node <------
      {:leaf, value} ->
        # with flat copy of the node structure <------
        {:leaf, value}
        # call handleCases <------
        |> then(handleCases)

      # inspect type of current node
      {:inner, inner_value, left, right} ->
        {
          # with flat copy of the node structure <------
          :inner,
          inner_value,
          # but with the recursive parts replaced by the recursion result <------
          reduceValue(left, handleCases),
          # but with the recursive parts replaced by the recursion result <------
          reduceValue(right, handleCases)
        }
        # call handleCases <------
        |> then(handleCases)
    end
  end
end

simpleBinaryTreeWithEmptyNode
|> SparseTreeReduceUnifiedReview.reduceValue(fn
  :empty -> :infinity
  {:leaf, v} -> v
  {:inner, v, l, r} -> min(v, min(l, r))
end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

Kino.nothing()
