```

*Wow!* All the `match` cases of the `reduceValue` are following exactly the same structure. Each time we just shallow-copy the node, replacing the recursive fields with the results of recursive function calls, and then we apply the `handleCases` function to the this flat copy of the node.

Could we extract the *make a flat copy of the node and replace the recursive parts* into a separate general function? **Yes we can!** Take a look:

```elixir
defmodule SparseTreeReplaceInner do
  # this function takes a tree and a replacer function
  # for non-recursive nodes it just returns the node
  # for recursive nodes it replaces the recursive parts via the replacer function
  def replaceInner(tree, replacer) do
    case tree do
      # inspect type of current node
      :empty ->
        # with flat copy of the node structure
        :empty

      # no |> then(handleCases) here anymore <------- !!!

      # inspect type of current node
      {:leaf, value} ->
        # with flat copy of the node structure
        {:leaf, value}

      # no |> then(handleCases) here anymore <------- !!!

      # inspect type of current node
      {:inner, inner_value, left, right} ->
        {
          # with flat copy of the node structure
          :inner,
          inner_value,
          # but with the recursive parts replaced by the recursion result
          replacer.(left),
          # but with the recursive parts replaced by the recursion result
          replacer.(right)
        }

        # no |> then(handleCases) here anymore <------- !!!
    end
  end

  # this function takes the tree and the handleCases from before
  # and makes use of the replaceInner function above
  # to replace each recursive fields in the tree
  # with the results of the recursive calculation
  def reduceValue(tree, handleCases) do
    tree
    |> replaceInner(fn
      # replace each child with its recursion result <------ !!!
      child -> reduceValue(child, handleCases)
    end)
    # call handleCases on the replacement result<------ !!!
    |> handleCases.()
  end
end

simpleBinaryTreeWithEmptyNode
# We can use it exactly as before
|> SparseTreeReduceUnifiedReview.reduceValue(fn
  :empty -> :infinity
  {:leaf, v} -> v
  {:inner, v, l, r} -> min(v, min(l, r))
end)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

Kino.nothing()
```

<!-- livebook:{"output":true} -->

```
Min Value: 4
```

Now look at that! The `SparseTreeReplaceInner.replaceInner` looks almost like our `Tree.processEachNode` function from the beginning, but instead of applying the callback function (`replacer`) to the `value` stored in a node, the function is applied to the *recursive fields* (`left` and `right`).

You might think of it as an alternative way implementation of `map` for `Tree` that kind of works across a different dimension. In this perspective a `Tree` node is just a tuple and the recursive dpeth is just accidental.

Also look at the `SparseTreeReplaceInner.reduceValue` function. *It is really short now!* The handling of all the cases has been moved into the  `SparseTreeReplaceInner.replaceInner` function. What is left in `SparseTreeReplaceInner.reduceValue` is the *pure essence of the recursion*. This is our codified recursion scheme!

Lets put everything back together:

## RecursiveReduction

```elixir
defmodule SparseTreeRecursionMap do
  # The recursive structure of a Tree is 
  # defined in terms of a mapping 
  # over the recursive fields
  def mapRecur(tree, fun) do
    case tree do
      :empty ->
        :empty

      {:leaf, value} ->
        {:leaf, value}

      {:inner, inner_value, left, right} ->
        {
          :inner,
          inner_value,
          fun.(left), # <-- fun.() is applied to the recursive fields
          fun.(right) # <-- fun.()
        }
    end
  end
end

# The recursive reduction
defmodule RecursiveReduction do
  # the recursive reduction makes use of the recursive structure to walk the
  # the tree. But now this reduce function is independent of any structure 
  # that is specific to list, tree or sparse tree
  def reduce(data, mapRecur, handleCases) do
    data
    |> mapRecur.(fn
      child -> reduce(child, mapRecur, handleCases)
    end)
    |> handleCases.()
  end
end

Kino.nothing()
```

After this refactoring we can use the `RecursiveReduction.reduce/2` function in combination with `SparseTreeRecursionMap.mapRecur` and an `handleCases` callback to calculate the minimum again.

```elixir
simpleBinaryTreeWithEmptyNode
|> RecursiveReduction.reduce(
  # We need to pass the mapRecure function that
  # know how to walk the recursive structure
  &SparseTreeRecursionMap.mapRecur/2,
  fn
    # the handleCases callback still needs to handle 
    # the cases specific the the processed data structure
    :empty -> :infinity
    {:leaf, v} -> v
    {:inner, v, l, r} -> min(v, min(l, r))
  end
)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

Kino.nothing()
```

