Now that we have codified the pattern that we discovered for `Tree`, we can repeat this for `LinkedList`. But note that the only difference is in the `mapRecur` function.
The `RecursiveReduction.reduce` is general and can just be reused.

```elixir
defmodule LinkedListRecursionMap do
  # the recursive structure of a singly linked list
  def mapRecur(tree, fun) do
    case tree do
      {} ->
        {}

      {head, tail} ->
        {
          head,
          fun.(tail) # <-- the fun.() call marks the recursive field
        }
    end
  end
end

# use the same reducer to find the minimum of the list
simpleLinkedList
|> RecursiveReduction.reduce(
  &LinkedListRecursionMap.mapRecur/2,
  fn
    # with the handleCases callback the tailored to the list structue
    {} -> :infinity
    {h, t} -> min(h, t)
  end
)
|> IO.inspect(label: "Min Value")

Kino.nothing()
